1 [Alt-Left and Alt-Right]
    move the cursor one word left or right,
    or moves forward/backward in the directory history if the command line is empty.

2 [Alt-Up and Alt-Down]
  search the command history for the previous/next token containing the token under the cursor before the search was started.

3 [Ctrl-C]
  deletes the entire line.

4 [Ctrl-D]
  delete one character to the right of the cursor.

5 [Ctrl-K]
  moves contents from the cursor to the end of line to the killring.

6 [Ctrl-U]
  moves contents from the beginning of line to the cursor to the killring.

7 [Ctrl-W]
  moves the previous word to the killring.

8 [Alt-D]
  moves the next word to the killring.

9 [Alt-W]
  prints a short description of the command under the cursor.

10 [Alt-L]
  lists the contents of the current directory, unless the cursor is over a
  directory argument, in which case the contents of that directory will be listed.

11 [Alt-P]
  adds the string '| less;' to the end of the job under the cursor. The result is that the output of the command will be paged.
  
12 [Alt-C]
  capitalizes the current word.

13 [Alt-U]
  makes the current word uppercase.
